<h1>None</h1>
<a href="/">Home</a>-<a href="/blog/index.html">blog</a>-<a href="/blog/2007/index.html">2007</a>-<a href="/blog/2007/02/index.html">02</a>-<a href="/blog/2007/02/16/index.html">16</a>
<div><p class="P1">At a recent RUBRIC meeting we discussed the idea that citation and copyright details need to be <b>on the actual documents</b> in a repository. Copyright statements in metadata don't mean much once the document has been downloaded and is 'in the wild', lost amongst 3000 documents called stuff like <code>item_8593.pdf</code>, most likely.</p><p>How about an automated way of summarizing document metadata and the relevant rights statement and adding it as a cover page to a PDF (or HTML document) in a repository? That way the user will be able to see what they've got when it's kicking around their hard disk. This should be easy enough to automate. Maybe it would make a good ARROW mini-project (strangely there's a <a href="http://www.arrow.edu.au/docs/files/ARROW_Mini-Projects_Scheme.txt">text doc</a> about these grants) if a developer wants to take it on.</p><p>A related idea is to store document metadata in the XMP metadata stream in a PDF. This was covered in what seems to be an unpublished paper (<a href="http://freelancepropaganda.com/archives/MP3vPDF.pdf">Howison 2004</a>) which pointed out that an iTunes like approach to managing PDFs would be very helpful. The <a href="http://www.zotero.org/">Zotero </a>research application should be able to do become iTunes for PDFs by recognizing and/or embedding metadata into your research library but as far as I can tell that's not yet a feature.</p><p></p><p></p><p></p></div>
